#### 15.1.3 Reporting Format (Paragraph 5.5.3)

The format for reporting transactions (including suspicious transactions made or attempted), as required under Rule 7(3) and Rule 8(2) of the PML Rules, shall be as prescribed by FIU-IND from time to time.

Reports submitted to FIU-IND shall contain complete and accurate information in respect of:

(a) Client KYC information;

(b) Wallet information;

(c) Transaction details;

(d) Counterparty information;

(e) Grounds of suspicion;

(f) Any other information prescribed by FIU-IND.

The Company shall use the FINGate portal or other reporting mechanisms prescribed by FIU-IND to submit STRs.

#### 15.1.4 Quality of STR Reporting (Paragraph 5.5.4)

Identification and reporting of STRs is an extremely serious obligation cast on the Company under the PMLA. The Company shall ensure that every STR is reported to FIU-IND only after due application of mind and after necessary diligence.

A prerequisite for high-quality STR reporting is ensuring that every data point available with the Company is effectively leveraged. This includes:

(a) KYC information;

(b) Transactional information;

(c) Technical and metadata information;

(d) IP Addresses;

(e) Device IDs;

(f) Any behavioural insights derived from the Company's monitoring systems.

The Company shall make serious efforts towards reporting high-quality STRs which serve as critical tools in detecting, deterring, and investigating the flow of illicit funds.

#### 15.1.5 STR Filing Irrespective of Threshold (Paragraph 5.5.5)

The Company shall file an STR, irrespective of the amount of transaction and any threshold limit envisaged for reporting under PMLA, if it has reasonable grounds to believe that the transaction involves proceeds of crime or financing of terrorism.

The absence of a monetary threshold for STR filing is fundamental to the Company's reporting obligation and shall be communicated clearly to all personnel involved in transaction monitoring and STR drafting.

#### 15.1.7 STR Workflow Capacity-Building (Operational Consideration)

Given the Company's nascent STR filing posture, the workflow set out in Section 15.1.6 is supplemented with the following capacity-building measures to ensure the Company's first and early STRs meet quality standards from the outset:

(a) **Pre-population of workflow templates:** The Company shall maintain pre-populated templates for STR investigation, narrative drafting, and supporting-evidence packaging, derived from FIU-IND-published guidance and industry-standard examples;

(b) **External consultation pathway:** The Principal Officer is authorised to consult with external AML/CFT/CPF professionals (subject to confidentiality protections) on early STR cases, particularly the first three to five STRs filed by the Company;

(c) **Extended internal review period:** Until the Company has filed at least ten STRs and demonstrated quality consistency, the internal review period before filing may be extended (within the regulatory seven-working-day window under Rule 8(2)) to allow careful drafting;

(d) **Post-filing self-review:** Each early STR shall be subject to documented self-review by the Principal Officer within 30 days of filing, identifying lessons learned and improvements to the workflow;

(e) **Conservative filing posture:** Where reasonable grounds for suspicion exist but the case is complex or borderline, the Principal Officer shall err toward filing (in accordance with Paragraph 5.5.5 of the 2026 Guidelines, which establishes that STRs are filed irrespective of threshold).

This capacity-building measure does not alter the substantive STR obligations under Rule 8(2) of the PML Rules — STRs continue to be required within seven working days of being satisfied that a transaction is suspicious.

#### 15.1.7 STR Workflow at Scale (Operational Consideration)

Given the Company's established STR filing record, the workflow set out in Section 15.1.6 is supplemented with the following operational measures to maintain quality and consistency at scale:

(a) **Workflow automation and case management:** The Company shall maintain a robust case management system that tracks each alert from detection through filing, with automated escalation timelines, deadline alerts, and audit trail integrity;

(b) **Tiered review structure:** Investigation, drafting, and review responsibilities shall be tiered across the AML/CFT/CPF team, with the Principal Officer retaining ultimate decision-making per Paragraph 3.3(e) of the 2026 Guidelines but able to delegate operational drafting to specialised personnel;

(c) **Quality assurance sampling:** A quality-assurance team or function (which may be the independent annual auditor or a designated internal audit function) shall periodically sample filed STRs to assess quality, consistency, and adherence to FIU-IND-published quality standards;

(d) **Pattern analysis and feedback integration:** The Principal Officer shall conduct quarterly review of STR filing patterns to identify systemic issues, gaps in alert coverage, and opportunities for transaction monitoring tuning;

(e) **External engagement:** Where FIU-IND publishes feedback (whether on a sectoral basis or on individual filings), the feedback shall be integrated into the workflow within 30 days;

(f) **Cross-functional escalation discipline:** Given the volume of STRs, cross-functional personnel (customer service, technology, operations) shall be trained on signal identification and structured escalation, to ensure all relevant data points reach the AML/CFT/CPF team for STR consideration.

### 15.2 Prohibition on Tipping-off

#### 15.2.1 Statutory and Regulatory Basis (Paragraph 5.6)

Section 12(2) and Section 12A(3) of the PMLA, read with Rule 8(6) of the PML Rules, require Reporting Entities, their directors, officers, and all employees (permanent as well as contractual) to ensure that the fact of maintenance of records and furnishing of information to FIU-IND is kept confidential.

In accordance with Paragraph 5.6 of the 2026 FIU-IND Guidelines, this prohibition on tipping-off extends not only to the filing of the STR and/or related information, but also to the period before, during, and after the submission of an STR.

#### 15.2.2 Scope of the Prohibition

The Company, its directors, officers, and all employees (permanent as well as contractual) shall ensure that there is no tipping-off to the client, the counterparty, or any other person at any level.

This prohibition applies to:

(a) The fact that the Company is considering filing an STR;

(b) The fact that the Company has filed an STR;

(c) The fact that the Company has received any information request from FIU-IND;

(d) The fact that the Company has received any information request from a law enforcement agency in relation to a client or transaction;

(e) The substance of any internal investigation into a suspicious transaction;

(f) Any details that may, directly or indirectly, alert the client or counterparty to the existence or content of an STR or related investigation.

#### 15.2.3 Operational Controls to Prevent Tipping-off

The Company shall implement operational controls to prevent tipping-off, including:

(a) Restricting access to STR-related information to personnel on a strict need-to-know basis;

(b) Ensuring that customer service personnel and front-line staff are trained never to disclose the existence of investigations, internal reviews, or compliance escalations to clients;

(c) Providing standard non-committal scripts for customer service personnel to use when clients enquire about account holds, freezes, or transaction delays attributable to AML/CFT/CPF compliance actions;

(d) Maintaining secure storage and transmission of all STR-related information, including access logs and audit trails;

(e) Including the tipping-off prohibition in employment contracts and confidentiality undertakings.

#### 15.2.4 Consequences of Tipping-off

Violation of the tipping-off prohibition constitutes a serious breach of the Company's AML/CFT/CPF obligations and may attract:

(a) Statutory penalties under the PMLA;

(b) Internal disciplinary action including termination of employment;

(c) Personal liability for the individual responsible, in addition to corporate liability for the Company.

#### 15.3.4 Pre-Established Section 12A Response Framework (Operational Consideration)

Given the Company's active engagement history with FIU-IND, the Section 12A response framework shall be operationally pre-established to enable rapid, high-quality responses. The framework shall include:

(a) **Designated response team:** A standing cross-functional team identified by name and role, covering AML/CFT/CPF (Principal Officer and team), technology (data extraction and forensic capability), legal (review and privilege considerations where relevant), and senior management (sign-off on time-sensitive responses);

(b) **Pre-staged data access:** Documented procedures and pre-tested data-extraction capability for common request types (transaction history for a client or wallet, KYC documents for a client, STR-related documents, sanctions screening logs, etc.);

(c) **Response timeline tracking:** A documented log of every Section 12A request received, the response deadline, the date and time of response, and any clarifications or follow-up exchanges. The log shall be reviewed quarterly by the Board or Board sub-committee;

(d) **Quality standards for responses:** Every Section 12A response shall be reviewed by the Principal Officer before submission, ensuring accuracy, completeness, and appropriate formatting;

(e) **Pattern analysis:** The Principal Officer shall analyse patterns in Section 12A requests received (request types, recurring client subjects, common typologies) to identify any systemic concerns and inform the Company's transaction monitoring and risk assessment frameworks.

#### 15.3.4 Section 12A Response Framework Establishment (Operational Consideration)

Given that the Company has not previously engaged with FIU-IND on Section 12A information requests, the Company shall proactively establish a Section 12A response framework to ensure operational readiness when the first such request is received. The framework establishment shall include:

(a) **Designated response team identification:** Identification of personnel who will be responsible for responding to Section 12A requests, with their roles and backup arrangements documented;

(b) **Capability assessment:** Documented assessment of the Company's data-extraction capabilities for likely request types, including transaction history extraction, KYC document retrieval, and STR-related documentation;

(c) **Procedural documentation:** Documented standard operating procedures for receipt, acknowledgement, internal routing, response drafting, internal review, and submission of Section 12A responses;

(d) **Mock response exercises:** At least one mock Section 12A response exercise per year, using hypothetical request scenarios, to validate operational readiness;

(e) **Periodic review:** Annual review of the framework by the Principal Officer to ensure it remains current with the Company's operational scale and any FIU-IND-published guidance on Section 12A processes.

This proactive framework establishment is intended to ensure that, when the Company first receives a Section 12A request, it can respond with the rigour and timeliness expected by FIU-IND.
